gs":["English: locative name, principally from from East or West Tuddenham (Norfolk), but also from Tuddenham (Suffolk) or Tuddenham Saint Martin (Suffolk)."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":26,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert Tudenham was born about 1264, in Oxborough, Norfolk, England, his father, Sir John Tudenham, was 23 and his mother, Joan Charles, was 29. He married Eve Peche in 1301, in Suffolk, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. He died on 17 April 1309, at the age of 46."},"et":{"about 1264–17 April 1309":"umbes 1264–17. aprill 1309","1264–1309":"1264–1309","1266–1318":"1266–1318","1260–1312":"1260–1312","1290–Male":"1290–Surnud","1295–1361":"1295–1361","1305–1332":"1305–1332","1242–1292":"1242–1292","1237–Female":"1237–Surnud","about 1290":"